HEADWORD: Incase
<hw>In*case"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Incased</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Incasing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>encaisser</ets>; pref.
<ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + <ets>caisse</ets> case. See
<er>Case</er> a box, and cf. <er>Encase</er>, <er>Enchase</er>.]</ety>
<def>To inclose in a case; to inclose; to cover or surround with
something solid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rich plates of gold the folding doors <qex>incase</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incasement</ent>⟦br⟧
